Unrestrained Central Bank Governor?
Prague — Recently, there has been one-sided criticism of central banks in developed countries, which has become fashionable.
The main points of criticism are roughly as follows: Since 2008, monetary policymakers have been too active, and their expanded authority has been growing too quickly, posing a risk to the economy.
This claim — strangely popular among ostensibly irreconcilable ideological camps, such as liberals and neo-Marxists — is deeply mistaken.
Critics have failed to understand that modern central banks are not only responsible for curbing inflation but also for maintaining long-term price stability.
The level of prices is like a person's body temperature, which can fluctuate within a range that is neither too high nor too low without causing serious symptoms.
When combating deflation caused by weak demand and curbing high inflation driven by excessive demand, central banks must be equally "proactive."
Although the battle was entirely symmetric, the public's assessment of it was inexplicably skewed, especially in countries where the people are financially conservative.
This includes my homeland, the Czech Republic. Czech savers have very small savings, and the loan-to-deposit ratio remains far below 100%.
Czechs are worried about inflation, even though inflation in the Czech Republic reached its lowest level in 13 years last year, and since 2013, when I have been serving as the Deputy Governor, the Czech National Bank has been committed to eliminating deflation risks.
Another common criticism of the monetary policies of developed countries' central banks since 2008 is that these policies have generated redistributive effects.
Of course it would, but so what?
Any monetary policy action redistributes wealth.
Raising interest rates pleases savers, while cutting interest rates benefits borrowers.
Importers prefer a strong exchange rate; exporters prefer a weak exchange rate.
For monetary policy to be effective, it must have different impacts on different groups at different times.
This is not an error; this is the essence of monetary policy.
Some critics also argue that central banks have failed to meet their inflation targets regardless, and thus their activism is not only unnecessary but also ineffective.
At times, they even place these contradictory criticisms into a single sentence, as if they were accusing someone of firing blanks yet causing casualties.
The reality is that central banks have successfully maintained price stability and the purchasing power of money during and after the global financial crisis — and this success is nothing short of remarkable.
Without their intervention, their economies would have faced catastrophic deflation, a sharp decline in asset prices, and a complete collapse of both the financial and real sectors.
Clearly, strong actions are the right approach to dealing with a crisis (the role of central banks in the outbreak of financial crises is another issue).
In a system that uses a flexible currency without intrinsic value, the quantity of money must change over time in order for the purchasing power of money to remain roughly constant.
Therefore, price stability, rather than the quantity of money, is the important issue.
The expansion of central bank balance sheets reflects the depth of problems faced by many economies after 2008.
Against this background, the central bank has taken necessary measures to maintain purchasing power and price stability.
For them, there is no such thing as "activism"; there is only the eternal mission of achieving a rightful status.
If you find this assertion to be arrogant, let me provide some evidence.
The people vote with their wallets.
If the purchasing power of their money was severely damaged after 2008, they would naturally seek to replace their local currency (with other currencies, precious metals, or other forms of savings).
This is rare in the developed world.
Of course, the central banks of many countries have not met their inflation targets.
(Central banks typically define the ideal economic "temperature" as an annual inflation rate of around 2%. )
However, although this is certainly unpleasant, it does not necessarily lead to a disaster, especially considering that the decline in prices is partly due to supply — rather than demand — shocks, such as a sharp drop in oil prices.
This shock benefits consumers and poses no threat to price stability, at least for net oil-importing countries.
Consider this scenario.
A company plans to increase its sales by 2%, but the manager achieves this goal by increasing sales by 1% each year for two consecutive years.
Do you think this company will fail?
I'm afraid not.
After all, private companies' planned versus actual profits and revenues can easily deviate by 10% or more.
Most businesses have fewer environmental variables than central banks.
If that's the case, how can you expect the central bank to always achieve precise inflation targets regardless of the economic environment?
It must be clarified that I did not say the central bank should not strive to work toward their goals.
They absolutely should.
Moreover, they should absolutely not allow inflation expectations to become unstable.
However, when evaluating the central bank, people need to maintain proper restraint.
They indeed need to stop saying untrue things — for example, the central bank's policy tool kit is not only potentially exhausted, but is already nearing exhaustion.
Monetary policymakers have ample tools and an unlimited supply of ammunition at their disposal to use as they see fit.
These weapons have different calibers and their effectiveness varies at different times.
Not all weapons are suitable for all situations in all economies.
But theoretically, the central bank's ability to create and destroy money is unlimited.
The central bank governor should tell the critics who are ignorant of the challenges they face, "Enough!"
None of our critics have been able to clearly and convincingly explain why price stability is an incorrect objective, what key objective the central bank should pursue, or what fundamentally different approach they should have taken since 2008.
There is a very simple reason for this: the policies adopted by central banks in developed countries since the crisis have been the correct ones.
In fact, this policy pulled our economy back from the brink.
You're welcome.
